  "raw_text": {
    "type": "doc",
    "attrs": {
      "meta": {},
      "suggestionId": null,
      "suggestionTimestamp": null,
      "suggestionUserId": null,
      "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
      "suggestionKind": null,
      "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
    },
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "nfleegmnyrn",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Humans do many things together collaboratively as joint agents or in groups as collective agents. It turns out that these ways of operating together as a \u201cwe\u201d have a number of special properties as compared with the cooperative interactions of other animal species. Most important are humans\u2019 special ways of thinking in terms of perspectives, their special ways of regulating social interactions normatively and morally, and the special ways that their cultural groups structure everything via conventions, norms, and institutions that ratchet up in complexity over historical time."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 1,
          "fixedId": "history",
          "id": "history",
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "History"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "noefw59qddg",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Beginning in the 1990s, the philosopher of action Michael Bratman ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nsqx4zhp746",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n17i6ivsy45\" data-reactroot=\"\">Bratman, M. E. (1992). Shared cooperative activity. <em>The</em> <em>Philosophical Review</em>, <em>101</em>(2), 327\u2013341. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.2307/2185537\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.2307/2185537</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "1992",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "n7iva0tukda",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"nr3dwt55a1y\" data-reactroot=\"\">Bratman, M. E. (2014). <em>Shared agency: A planning theory of acting together</em>. Oxford University Press. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199897933.001.0001\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199897933.001.0001</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "2014",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ") identified what he called "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "shared cooperative activities"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and outlined some of the unique psychological processes at work when two people paint a house together or cook a meal together collaboratively. The philosopher of intentionality John Searle ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nt95n1oovcl",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"nsncxwm3w9l\" data-reactroot=\"\">Searle, J. R. (1995). <em>The construction of social reality</em>. The Free Press.</p>",
              "customLabel": "1995",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "ngdeawj5hly",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"np20bbjzihp\" data-reactroot=\"\">Searle, J. R. (2010). <em>Making the social world: The structure of human civilization.</em> Oxford University Press. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1093/acprof:osobl/9780195396171.001.0001\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.1093/acprof:osobl/9780195396171.001.0001</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "2010",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ") identified what he called "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "collective intentionality"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and outlined some of the unique psychological processes at work when groups of people collectively recognize a comrade as a president or a piece of paper as money."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "ni8yxka01ch",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In the early 2000s, "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nmdazn4jd8a",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"nflp8vefdk3\" data-reactroot=\"\">Tomasello, M., &amp; Rakoczy, H. (2003). What makes human cognition unique? From individual to shared to collective intentionality. <em>Mind &amp; Language</em>,<em> 18</em>(2), 121\u2013147. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0017.00217\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0017.00217</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Tomasello and Rakoczy (2003)",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "ndmgnu47m2o",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n10ilqh0pc2\" data-reactroot=\"\">Tomasello, M., Carpenter, M., Call, J., Behne, T., &amp; Moll, H. (2005). Understanding and sharing intentions: The origins of cultural cognition. <em>Behavioral and Brain Sciences</em>,<em> 28</em>(5), 675\u2013691. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1017/S0140525X05000129\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.1017/S0140525X05000129</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Tomasello et al. (2005)",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " investigated how these processes of shared intentionality emerged in human evolution and how they emerge in human ontogeny [see "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "link",
                "attrs": {
                  "href": "https://oecs.mit.edu/pub/zw60p83x",
                  "title": null,
                  "target": null,
                  "pubEdgeId": null
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "Cognitive Development"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "]. Tomasello ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nf1iguqpx9k",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"nybbsfjowqs\" data-reactroot=\"\">Tomasello, M. (2014). <em>A natural history of human thinking</em>. Harvard University Press. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.4159/9780674726369\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.4159/9780674726369</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "2014",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nprmkoxkgk2",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"ngqww4rp8p7\" data-reactroot=\"\">Tomasello, M. (2016).\u00a0<em>A natural history of human morality</em>. Harvard University Press. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.4159/9780674915855\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.4159/9780674915855</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "2016",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "n0bmqia4709",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n3eexhlbru8\" data-reactroot=\"\">Tomasello, M. (2019). <em>Becoming human: A theory of ontogeny.</em> Harvard University Press. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.4159/9780674988651\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.4159/9780674988651</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "2019",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ") distinguished between "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "joint intentionality"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", involving individuals collaborating with one another, and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "collective intentionality"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", involving individuals interacting within a cultural group structured by cultural conventions, norms, and institutions. The proposal is that these processes are unique to humans\u2014because at some point in human evolution individuals became interdependent with one another for survival\u2014and they are responsible for humans\u2019 unique forms of cooperation and cultural organization. Tomasello ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nx9t8oggig3",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n6halgidmes\" data-reactroot=\"\">Tomasello, M. (2022). <em>The evolution of agency: Behavioral Organization from lizards to humans.</em> MIT Press. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.7551/mitpress/14238.001.0001\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.7551/mitpress/14238.001.0001</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "2022",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nx2j1bj8fsq",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"nbwhmdhcsof\" data-reactroot=\"\">Tomasello, M. (2024). <em>Agency and cognitive development.</em> Oxford University Press. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1093/9780191998294.001.0001\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.1093/9780191998294.001.0001</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "2024",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ") argued that the broadest perspective on these phenomena is in terms of human agency: humans (and only humans) form "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "joint agencies"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "collective agencies"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 1,
          "fixedId": "core-concepts",
          "id": "core-concepts",
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Core concepts"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "nkhugc822cm",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "To form a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "joint agency"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " with a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "joint goal"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", each participant must have the goal that they act together, and they must also know together in "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "common ground"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " that they both share this goal. Each partner has their own individual "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "role"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " in the joint agency that they must "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "coordinate"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " with their partner\u2019s role. Working together toward a joint goal requires "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "joint attention"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to things relevant to the joint goal, with each partner having their own individual perspective. In the ideal case, participants engage in "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "cooperative communication"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (acts aimed at informing the partner of things helpful to their role) to facilitate a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "joint decision"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Participants may be tempted to opt out of the joint agency and so may begin by making a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "joint commitment"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (A: \u201cWant to X?\u201d; B: \u201cSure\u201d), which entitles each of them to rebuke the other normatively for not playing their role in the ideal way or for not sharing the spoils of the joint activity in a manner "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "fair"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to both (\u201cYou should/should not X\u201d; "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nbr8awm34gk",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n6o4tw0cklh\" data-reactroot=\"\">Gilbert, M. (2003). The structure of the social atom: Joint commitment as the foundation of human social behavior. In F. Schmitt (Ed.), <em>Socializing metaphysics</em> (pp. 39\u201364). Rowman &amp; Littlefield. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.5771/9780585466651-39\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.5771/9780585466651-39</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Gilbert, 2003",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "ncsxl3z371q",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"ndz0i1q332y\" data-reactroot=\"\">Gilbert, M. (2014). <em>Joint commitment: How we make the social world</em>. Oxford University Press. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199970148.001.0001\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199970148.001.0001</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "2014",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ")."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "n4qe051tpay",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Human groups may form "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "collective agencies"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "\u2014prototypically cultural groups\u2014with "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "collective goals"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " based in "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "collective "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "(or"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": " cultural"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ")"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": " common ground."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " To facilitate coordination among in-group strangers, groups develop "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "conventions"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "\u2014including "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "communicative "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "("
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "linguistic"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ")"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": " conventions"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "\u2014to which individuals simply "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "conform"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". To become a full-fledged member of a cultural group, individuals join into a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "collective commitment"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "social norms"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " of the group, which "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "obligates"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " them not only to conform but to engage in "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "norm enforcement"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to make sure that others conform as well ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nbb217s4gpi",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"nsanfl9o2ui\" data-reactroot=\"\">Tomasello, M. (2020). The moral psychology of obligation. <em>Behavioral and Brain Sciences</em>,<em> 43</em>, e56. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1017/S0140525X19001742\">https://doi.org/10.1017/S0140525X19001742</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Tomasello, 2020",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ") [see "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "link",
                "attrs": {
                  "href": "https://oecs.mit.edu/pub/sr3246n4",
                  "title": null,
                  "target": null,
                  "pubEdgeId": null
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "Normativity"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "]. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Cultural"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "institutions"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " are organized collections of social roles and norms for specific societal purposes. Failure to join into a collective commitment to the norms of the group leads to a loss of one\u2019s "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "cooperative identity"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " in the group. Adults in a cultural group instruct youngsters with prosocially motivated and normatively framed "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "pedagogy"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (\u201cthis is how it should be done\u201d), to which youngsters normatively conform, leading to a cultural "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "ratchet effect"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " in which both material and symbolic artifacts (from spears to language) increase in complexity over cultural-historical time [see "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "link",
                "attrs": {
                  "href": "https://oecs.mit.edu/pub/u870vxpu",
                  "title": null,
                  "target": null,
                  "pubEdgeId": null
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "Cultural Evolution"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "]."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 1,
          "fixedId": "questions-controversies-and-new-developments",
          "id": "questions-controversies-and-new-developments",
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Questions, controversies, and new developments"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "nknzygl0arf",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Many comparative studies have purported to show that shared agency and intentionality are unique to humans among primates, suggesting further that this fact explains how and why only humans have come to live in cultural groups that create and maintain complex cultural artifacts and practices based on cultural conventions, norms, and institutions [see "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "link",
                "attrs": {
                  "href": "https://oecs.mit.edu/pub/rbmlimm5",
                  "title": null,
                  "target": null,
                  "pubEdgeId": null
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "Animal Cognition"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "]. Other researchers have disputed this claim with comparative studies suggesting that nonhuman great apes (especially chimpanzees and orangutans) may also live in cultures, form joint and collective agencies, make joint commitments, engage in joint attention, create conventions and norms, and communicate cooperatively and even linguistically (see "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nngswr4lq3g",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"ntzujd1xtoy\" data-reactroot=\"\">Heesen, R., &amp; Fr\u00f6hlich, M. (2022). Revisiting the human \u2018interaction engine\u2019: Comparative approaches to social action coordination. <em>Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society</em> <em>B</em>, <em>377</em>, 20210092. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1098/rstb.2021.0092\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.1098/rstb.2021.0092</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Heesen & Fr\u00f6hlich, 2022",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "). If nonhuman great apes do in fact engage in all these shared intentional activities, it is unclear why this has not led to their creating human-like cultural artifacts and practices."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "n3xxp82wu49",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The newest developments in shared intentionality theory explain the evolution and development of individual psychological processes in terms of the evolution and development of agentive action and its control system organization: organisms make cognitively informed decisions to produce adaptive goal-directed actions, which are naturally selected ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nlu3feos0ge",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"nu2a7qmoe07\" data-reactroot=\"\">Tomasello, M. (2022). <em>The evolution of agency: Behavioral Organization from lizards to humans.</em> MIT Press. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.7551/mitpress/14238.001.0001\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.7551/mitpress/14238.001.0001</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Tomasello, 2022",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "n0chha3sk8b",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"nbwhmdhcsof\" data-reactroot=\"\">Tomasello, M. (2024). <em>Agency and cognitive development.</em> Oxford University Press. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1093/9780191998294.001.0001\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.1093/9780191998294.001.0001</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "2024",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "). This foundation prepares for a smooth transition evolutionarily and developmentally to human shared agency, in which individuals coordinate their individual psychological agencies to produce adaptive social and cultural actions. Humans\u2019 adaptations for functioning as both individual and shared agents are responsible for many or most of humans\u2019 unique psychological capacities."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 1,
          "fixedId": "broader-connections",
          "id": "broader-connections",
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Broader connections"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "nsh4cpbto0v",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Traditionally, cognitive psychology and cognitive science have focused on the individual and their individual cognitive processes. The argument from shared intentionality theory is that many of humans\u2019 most powerful cognitive processes came into existence evolutionarily and come into existence ontogenetically, in order to deal with the challenges of human social and cultural life. These include recursive thinking (to coordinate with others in shared agencies), objective thinking (to resolve perspectival disputes with others), and sociomoral and normative concepts and attitudes (to resolve preference disputes with others). Moreover, humans could not function as they do cognitively without collectively produced cultural products, beginning most importantly with language but also including other symbolic artifacts such as Arabic numerals and material artifacts of various kinds, from bows and arrows to telephones and computers [see "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "link",
                "attrs": {
                  "href": "https://oecs.mit.edu/pub/ho9e9c80",
                  "title": null,
                  "target": null,
                  "pubEdgeId": null
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "Language"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "]. The perspective from shared intentionality thus provides a bridge from psychology and cognitive science to surrounding fields in the behavioral and social sciences, from anthropology to legal studies."
          }
        ]
      },
